    {
      "id": "st-topic-fcf1fd0d",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "**🪜 Telemetry Ingestion and Normalization**\n\n10 steps\n\n**Checkpoints:**\n• After Step 2: Can you explain the difference between metrics, logs, and traces in your own words to a non-technical friend?\n• After Step 4: Can you trace through the flow of a single log event, identifying where normalization occurs and what data is transformed?",
      "x": -200,
      "y": 2840,
      "width": 280,
      "height": 200,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
      "id": "st-fcf1fd0d-0",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "**Step 1**\n\nStep 1: Understand — Define the fundamental problem that Telemetry Ingestion and Normalization solves (the 'why' behind observability).",
      "x": 110,
      "y": 2840,
      "width": 280,
      "height": 130,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
      "id": "st-fcf1fd0d-1",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "**Step 2**\n\nStep 2: Learn — Define the core vocabulary, including metrics, logs, traces, schema, and vendor-agnosticism.",
      "x": 420,
      "y": 2840,
      "width": 280,
      "height": 130,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
      "id": "st-fcf1fd0d-2",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "**Step 3**\n\nStep 3: Grasp — Analyze the core mechanism of the pipeline: how raw signals flow from diverse sources into a unified, standardized format.",
      "x": 730,
      "y": 2840,
      "width": 280,
      "height": 130,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
      "id": "st-fcf1fd0d-3",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "**Step 4**\n\nStep 4: Trace — Trace through a minimal example of a single signal (e.g., a metric) from source to final storage, focusing on the normalization step.",
      "x": 1040,
      "y": 2840,
      "width": 280,
      "height": 130,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
      "id": "st-fcf1fd0d-4",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "**Step 5**\n\nStep 5: Identify — Identify the key components and their interactions (e.g., agents, queues, processors, schema registries) in a typical ingestion architecture.",
      "x": 1350,
      "y": 2840,
      "width": 280,
      "height": 130,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
      "id": "st-fcf1fd0d-5",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "**Step 6**\n\nStep 6: Study — Study the most common real-world use cases and patterns (e.g., handling high cardinality, sampling strategies, and correlation of metrics, logs, and traces).",
      "x": 1660,
      "y": 2840,
      "width": 280,
      "height": 130,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
      "id": "st-fcf1fd0d-6",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "**Step 7**\n\nStep 7: Learn — Learn what can go wrong: identify common failure modes related to data loss, semantic drift, and temporal correlation issues.",
      "x": 1970,
      "y": 2840,
      "width": 280,
      "height": 130,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
      "id": "st-fcf1fd0d-7",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "**Step 8**\n\nStep 8: Explore — Explore the variations in implementation: compare different normalization standards (e.g., Prometheus format vs. OpenTelemetry semantic model) and ingestion technologies (e.g., Kafka vs. direct push).",
      "x": 2280,
      "y": 2840,
      "width": 280,
      "height": 130,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
      "id": "st-topic-87a7d9a8",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "**🪜 Semantic Signal Enrichment**\n\n10 steps\n\n**Checkpoints:**\n• After Step 2: Can you explain the difference between a raw metric and a semantically enriched signal to a non-technical stakeholder?\n• After Step 4: Can you trace the flow of context (dependencies, SLOs) from raw data to the final actionable signal without looking at notes?",
      "x": -200,
      "y": 3190,
      "width": 280,
      "height": 200,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
      "id": "st-87a7d9a8-0",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "**Step 1**\n\nStep 1: Understand — Define the core problem Semantic Signal Enrichment solves: why raw telemetry is insufficient and the pain points of operating without context.",
      "x": 110,
      "y": 3190,
      "width": 280,
      "height": 130,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
      "id": "st-87a7d9a8-1",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "**Step 2**\n\nStep 2: Learn — Define the essential vocabulary, focusing on terms like SLOs, Error Budgets, Service Dependencies, and Telemetry.",
      "x": 420,
      "y": 3190,
      "width": 280,
      "height": 130,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
      "id": "st-87a7d9a8-2",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "**Step 3**\n\nStep 3: Grasp — Analyze the core mechanism: how raw metrics are transformed into context-rich, actionable signals through the addition of metadata.",
      "x": 730,
      "y": 3190,
      "width": 280,
      "height": 130,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
      "id": "st-87a7d9a8-3",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "**Step 4**\n\nStep 4: Trace — Trace through a minimal example: walk through the process of enriching a simple response time metric with dependency and SLO context.",
      "x": 1040,
      "y": 3190,
      "width": 280,
      "height": 130,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
      "id": "st-87a7d9a8-4",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "**Step 5**\n\nStep 5: Identify — Identify the necessary components: determine what data sources (e.g., service mesh, deployment manifests, incident systems) are needed and how they interact.",
      "x": 1350,
      "y": 3190,
      "width": 280,
      "height": 130,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
      "id": "st-87a7d9a8-5",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "**Step 6**\n\nStep 6: Study — Study the most common real-world use cases and patterns: examine how enrichment is applied in dependency mapping, anomaly detection, and incident prioritization.",
      "x": 1660,
      "y": 3190,
      "width": 280,
      "height": 130,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
      "id": "st-87a7d9a8-6",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "**Step 7**\n\nStep 7: Explore — Explore the failure modes: identify common pitfalls, such as stale dependency data, incorrect SLO calculations, and broken historical associations.",
      "x": 1970,
      "y": 3190,
      "width": 280,
      "height": 130,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
      "id": "st-87a7d9a8-7",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "**Step 8**\n\nStep 8: Connect — Connect it to adjacent concepts: understand how Semantic Signal Enrichment relates to traditional monitoring, observability, SLO management, and graph databases.",
      "x": 2280,
      "y": 3190,
      "width": 280,
      "height": 130,
      "color": "2"
    },
    {
